10.12 Core Diagnostic Patterns
These four query patterns apply to any table in any database:
Missingness: SELECT col, COUNT(*) - COUNT(col) AS n_null FROM table;
Duplicates: SELECT key_cols, COUNT(*) AS n FROM table GROUP BY key_cols HAVING n &gt; 1;
Inconsistent categories: SELECT col, COUNT(*) FROM table GROUP BY col ORDER BY COUNT(*) DESC;
Invalid ranges: SELECT MIN(col), MAX(col), AVG(col) FROM table;

17.6 XML
XML (eXtensible Markup Language) is older and more verbose than JSON but still common in government filings (SEC EDGAR, congressional records) and scientific data.

raw = '''&lt;?xml version="1.0"?&gt;
&lt;catalog&gt;
  &lt;book id="1"&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Information Exploration&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;year&gt;2026&lt;/year&gt;
  &lt;/book&gt;
  &lt;book id="2"&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Tidy Data&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;year&gt;2014&lt;/year&gt;
  &lt;/book&gt;
&lt;/catalog&gt;'''

root = ET.fromstring(raw)
for book in root.findall('book'):
    print(book.get('id'), book.find('title').text, book.find('year').text)

Two key methods: .find(tag) returns the first child with a matching tag; .findall(tag) returns all of them. Attributes (id="1") are accessed with .get(); text content is on the .text property.
For complex XML documents — SEC filings, government records — consider lxml or the xmltodict library, which converts XML to nested dicts that pd.json_normalize can handle.
